[
    {
        "content": "<p>A framed bicategory/proarrow equipment/fibrant double category is one such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mover><mo stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"3.0em\">→</mo><mpadded width=\"+0.6em\" lspace=\"0.3em\"><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mpadded></mover><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_1 \\xrightarrow{(s,t)} C_0 \\times C_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.297em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel x-arrow\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.147em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.322em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight x-arrow-pad\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">s</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-2.689em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"height:0.522em;min-width:1.469em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='0.522em' viewBox='0 0 400000 522' preserveAspectRatio='xMaxYMin slice'><path d='M0 241v40h399891c-47.3 35.3-84 78-110 128\n-16.7 32-27.7 63.7-33 95 0 1.3-.2 2.7-.5 4-.3 1.3-.5 2.3-.5 3 0 7.3 6.7 11 20\n 11 8 0 13.2-.8 15.5-2.5 2.3-1.7 4.2-5.5 5.5-11.5 2-13.3 5.7-27 11-41 14.7-44.7\n 39-84.5 73-119.5s73.7-60.2 119-75.5c6-2 9-5.7 9-11s-3-9-9-11c-45.3-15.3-85\n-40.5-119-75.5s-58.3-74.8-73-119.5c-4.7-14-8.3-27.3-11-40-1.3-6.7-3.2-10.8-5.5\n-12.5-2.3-1.7-7.5-2.5-15.5-2.5-14 0-21 3.7-21 11 0 2 2 10.3 6 25 20.7 83.3 67\n 151.7 139 205zm0 0v40h399900v-40z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a fibration, and this amounts to having all companions and conjoints in the double category.<br>\nIs there a similar characterization for double categories with all companions? I can't think of an obvious one on my two feet. It seems that asking for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span></span></span></span> to be a fibration should be enough, but pulling back a loose map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> along a tight map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A&#x27; \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> might yield a square whose bottom map isn't necessarily the loose unit, unless I'm missing something.</p>",
        "id": 418842440,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706623627
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A double category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> may also be characterised as having all companions if there exists a pseudo double functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">S</mi><mi>q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{S}q(C_{0}) \\rightarrow \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> that is the identity on objects and tight morphisms.</p>",
        "id": 418846133,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1706624723
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah but I was hoping for something more 'formal', i.e. that I can express for internal categories more generally</p>",
        "id": 418846382,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706624791
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The condition I gave can be expressed for any pseudo-category object in a $2$-category with comma objects.</p>",
        "id": 418846546,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1706624832
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are probably other nice characterisations though</p>",
        "id": 418846890,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1706624924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think I found it by the way: a double category has companions iff the span <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mover><mo stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"3.0em\">←</mo><mpadded width=\"+0.6em\" lspace=\"0.3em\"><mi>s</mi></mpadded></mover><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mover><mo stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"3.0em\">→</mo><mpadded width=\"+0.6em\" lspace=\"0.3em\"><mi>t</mi></mpadded></mover><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_0 \\xleftarrow{s} C_1 \\xrightarrow{t} C_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0734em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel x-arrow\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9234em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.322em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight x-arrow-pad\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">s</span></span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-2.689em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"height:0.522em;min-width:1.469em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='0.522em' viewBox='0 0 400000 522' preserveAspectRatio='xMinYMin slice'><path d='M400000 241H110l3-3c68.7-52.7 113.7-120\n 135-202 4-14.7 6-23 6-25 0-7.3-7-11-21-11-8 0-13.2.8-15.5 2.5-2.3 1.7-4.2 5.8\n-5.5 12.5-1.3 4.7-2.7 10.3-4 17-12 48.7-34.8 92-68.5 130S65.3 228.3 18 247\nc-10 4-16 7.7-18 11 0 8.7 6 14.3 18 17 47.3 18.7 87.8 47 121.5 85S196 441.3 208\n 490c.7 2 1.3 5 2 9s1.2 6.7 1.5 8c.3 1.3 1 3.3 2 6s2.2 4.5 3.5 5.5c1.3 1 3.3\n 1.8 6 2.5s6 1 10 1c14 0 21-3.7 21-11 0-2-2-10.3-6-25-20-79.3-65-146.7-135-202\n l-3-3h399890zM100 241v40h399900v-40z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2026em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel x-arrow\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.0526em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.322em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight x-arrow-pad\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span></span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-2.689em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"height:0.522em;min-width:1.469em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='0.522em' viewBox='0 0 400000 522' preserveAspectRatio='xMaxYMin slice'><path d='M0 241v40h399891c-47.3 35.3-84 78-110 128\n-16.7 32-27.7 63.7-33 95 0 1.3-.2 2.7-.5 4-.3 1.3-.5 2.3-.5 3 0 7.3 6.7 11 20\n 11 8 0 13.2-.8 15.5-2.5 2.3-1.7 4.2-5.5 5.5-11.5 2-13.3 5.7-27 11-41 14.7-44.7\n 39-84.5 73-119.5s73.7-60.2 119-75.5c6-2 9-5.7 9-11s-3-9-9-11c-45.3-15.3-85\n-40.5-119-75.5s-58.3-74.8-73-119.5c-4.7-14-8.3-27.3-11-40-1.3-6.7-3.2-10.8-5.5\n-12.5-2.3-1.7-7.5-2.5-15.5-2.5-14 0-21 3.7-21 11 0 2 2 10.3 6 25 20.7 83.3 67\n 151.7 139 205zm0 0v40h399900v-40z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a <em>left fibration</em> in the sense of <a href=\"http://www.numdam.org/article/CTGDC_1980__21_2_111_0.pdf\">Street</a>. This means <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span></span></span></span> is a fibration <em>and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> inverts <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span></span></span></span>-cartesian morphisms</em>, which means that the target of a cartesian square has to be an isomorphism, which is as close to an identity as I can possibly hope to get.<br>\nI suspect conjoints amount to the span being a <em>right fibration</em>, and then having both means being a two-sided fibration (a thing which, IIRC, it's in Shulman's paper already if one remembers the characterization of two-sided fibrations as fibrations over the product)</p>",
        "id": 418847034,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706624961
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276693\">Bryce Clarke</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/fibrancy.20of.20double.20categories.20with.20companions/near/418846546\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The condition I gave can be expressed for any pseudo-category object in a $2$-category with comma objects.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Uhm indeed, I dismissed it too quickly...</p>",
        "id": 418847147,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706624997
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Having such a functor means having a 2-cell in the double category of spans as follows: <br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/D4PBt-Kr-Xn7CSNuTuwbAp1F/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/D4PBt-Kr-Xn7CSNuTuwbAp1F/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/D4PBt-Kr-Xn7CSNuTuwbAp1F/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 418848355,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706625321
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which makes <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> into a <a href=\"https://www.epatters.org/post/algebras-are-promonads\">promonad</a> in Span</p>",
        "id": 418848668,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706625394
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Incidentally, this is actually the thing I was trying to get to, so thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276693\">@Bryce Clarke</span> <span aria-label=\"grinning face with smiling eyes\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f601\" role=\"img\" title=\"grinning face with smiling eyes\">:grinning_face_with_smiling_eyes:</span></p>",
        "id": 418848772,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706625421
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I haven't thought about it in that way before, cool! Thanks for the link to Evan's blog post too.</p>",
        "id": 418850101,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1706625781
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed, I think by Proposition 1 in <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275965\">@Evan Patterson</span>'s post I linked above, we see that the two descriptions we found are equivalent. This is because Evan there proves that (I'm going to translate his result into this specific instance), alternatively, a promonad on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> can be presented as a pair of loose monads (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>↓</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^\\downarrow</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">↓</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> in my case) such that the second is a left module over the first. But being a left module over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>↓</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^\\downarrow</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">↓</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is the definition of left fibration!</p>",
        "id": 418850324,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706625834
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm giggling because I was kicking myself for spending an hour this morning reading Evan's post and playing with promonads instead of working, then this afternoon I work and this pops up... call it providence!</p>",
        "id": 418850796,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706625957
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just found out this remark in <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span>'s paper on framed bicategories: <br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/xRyrybZuxoIUas1sVpby25IW/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\nSo my conjecture is wrong in some way. I suspect that left fibrancy only buys you (the universal property of) the counit of the companionship, and that one needs the span to be a <em>left bifibration</em> to also get a cocartesian cell witnessing the unit.<br>\nThen a right bifibration gives conjoints, and a two-sided fibration is a proarrow equipment.</p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/xRyrybZuxoIUas1sVpby25IW/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/xRyrybZuxoIUas1sVpby25IW/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 418872888,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706631261
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The span being a two-sided fibration is precisely the condition you need to get <em>companions</em> only.  To also have conjoints you need it to also be a two-sided fibration in the other direction.</p>",
        "id": 418883076,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1706634342
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, actually, I don't know whether something weaker than a full two-sided fibration <em>suffices</em> to get companions due to the double-categorical structure.  But a double category with only companions <em>is</em> a two-sided fibration, and conversely, so if so then that weaker structure would (in the case of a double category) imply a two-sided fibration.</p>",
        "id": 418883361,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1706634415
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Might be worth mentioning that <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275899\">@Christian Williams</span> pointed out this characterisation of double categories with companions or conjoints respectively in <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/exponentiable.20double.20categories/near/410453084\">https://categorytheory.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/exponentiable.20double.20categories/near/410453084</a>.)</p>",
        "id": 418901224,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1706641011
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/fibrancy.20of.20double.20categories.20with.20companions/near/418850324\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Indeed, I think by Proposition 1 in <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275965\">Evan Patterson</span>'s post I linked above, we see that the two descriptions we found are equivalent. This is because Evan there proves that (I'm going to translate his result into this specific instance), alternatively, a promonad on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> can be presented as a pair of loose monads (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>↓</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^\\downarrow</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">↓</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> in my case) such that the second is a left module over the first. But being a left module over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>↓</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^\\downarrow</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">↓</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is the definition of left fibration!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So here I was being too hasty... <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> would actually be a bimodule (that's what profunctor means <span aria-label=\"face palm\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f926\" role=\"img\" title=\"face palm\">:face_palm:</span> ) for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>↓</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^\\downarrow</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">↓</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, hence a two-sided fbration</p>",
        "id": 418986345,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1706688651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276693\">Bryce Clarke</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/fibrancy.20of.20double.20categories.20with.20companions/near/418846133\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A double category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> may also be characterised as having all companions if there exists a pseudo double functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">S</mi><mi>q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{S}q(C_{0}) \\rightarrow \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> that is the identity on objects and tight morphisms.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276693\">@Bryce Clarke</span>, do you have a reference for this statement? I know your thesis has the variant that a functorial choice of companions gives a <em>strict</em> double functor of the above form, but I couldn't immediately locate the quoted characterization in the literature.</p>",
        "id": 420186023,
        "sender_full_name": "Evan Patterson",
        "timestamp": 1707285285
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I do not have a reference for this statement. I was simply relaxing the strict version of the statement from my thesis. It doesn't seem to be written down in the early Grandis-Paré papers either, although it would not surprise me if it is written down somewhere in the double category theory literature. However, to me at least, this feels closer to an observation than a proposition.</p>",
        "id": 420190016,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1707288224
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The nlab page for <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/companion%20pairs\">[[companion pairs]]</a> has the following statement: </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If every vertical arrow in some double category D has a companion, then the functor $f \\mapsto f_{\\ast*}$$ is a pseudofunctor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi>D</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>H</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">VD \\rightarrow HD</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">HD</span></span></span></span> from the vertical 2-category to the horizontal one, which is the identity on objects, and locally fully faithful by the mate correspondence.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 420190351,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1707288449
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As an aside, I think the nlab pages for <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/companion%20pairs\">[[companion pairs]]</a> and <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/conjunction\">[[conjunction]]</a>  (why not conjoint pairs?) could use a bit of updating. I might add this to my todo list, but anyone reading this should feel encouraged to make edits too.</p>",
        "id": 420190680,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1707288719
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I also wonder if anyone is brave enough to change every instance of <em>vertical</em> and <em>horizontal</em> on the nlab to <em>tight</em> or <em>loose</em> (as appropriate). It is impossible to use the convention of horizontal vs. vertical consistently (after all, many concepts in double category theory are introduced in different papers which have different conventions).</p>",
        "id": 420191111,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1707289051
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for clarification, Bryce. I agree with you that this result should not be hard to prove. I think it's not entirely trivial, though: one needs to use the sliding correspondence for companions to furnish the action on cells, then do calculations to show that this is suitably functorial and pseudofunctorial. It might run to some length if spelled out in any detail. But ultimately routine, yes.</p>",
        "id": 420191129,
        "sender_full_name": "Evan Patterson",
        "timestamp": 1707289058
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks also for the pointer to the related characterization on nLab. It makes me suspect that these two results can be combined to characterize the presence of companions by the existence of an identity-on-objects-and-arrows (pseudo) double functor from the double category of quintets in the underlying 2-category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> to the double category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> itself. That statement would pack quite a lot of information about what you can do with companions!</p>",
        "id": 420191748,
        "sender_full_name": "Evan Patterson",
        "timestamp": 1707289463
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275965\">Evan Patterson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/fibrancy.20of.20double.20categories.20with.20companions/near/420191748\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks also for the pointer to the related characterization on nLab. It makes me suspect that these two results can be combined to characterize the presence of companions by the existence of an identity-on-objects-and-arrows (pseudo) double functor from the double category of quintets in the underlying 2-category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> to the double category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> itself. That statement would pack quite a lot of information about what you can do with companions!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I agree that this characterisation seems very likely. In cases like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Span</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Sp</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">an</span></span></span></span> it amounts to the same thing, but in cases like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Prof</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ro</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> it would appear to carry a bit more information.</p>",
        "id": 420192863,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1707290186
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275965\">@Evan Patterson</span> Perhaps this result is really about a coreflective adjunction between the category of 2-categories and unitary pseudofunctors (those which preserve identities strictly) and the category of (pseudo) double categories with companions and unitary double functors. I guess this is almost what theorem 1.7 of \"Limits in double categories\" says.</p>",
        "id": 420204943,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryce Clarke",
        "timestamp": 1707296220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice connection, I'll have to think about that. Thanks! (For anyone else following, the paper in question in \"Adjoint for double categories.\")</p>",
